# ORCA Medication Tracking — Working Notes

Callan and Nico have been sketching the buprenorphine medication tracking workflow at ORCA. This is a snapshot for shared reference — problem, current-state cartoon, draft user stories, a vocabulary sketch, and open questions. Meant to be edited.

---

## 1. Problem statement

ORCA tracks buprenorphine medications — long-acting injectables, tablets, and films — through a fully paper-based process. Kelley-Ross delivers; ORCA staff sign meds in on paper Controlled Substance Records (CSRs) using two-signature authentication, file them in cabinets and drawers organized alphabetically by patient last name, and sign them back out as patients arrive or as staff transport them to permanent supportive housing (PSH) sites.

The workflow functions, but several things are hard:

- **Knowing where a given medication is** — at ORCA, at one of several PSH sites, or in transit
- **Reconciling two paper records** — meds signed out at ORCA must also be signed into a separate paper CSR at the PSH site
- **Knowing when to reorder** — currently triggered by an empty folder, or by Kelley-Ross prompting for injectables
- **Keeping the CSR usable for non-clinical frontline staff** — providers, nurses, MAs, and milieu specialists all interact with it
- **Meeting DEA and pharmacy regulatory requirements** — any electronic replacement has to satisfy these

ORCA has no functional EHR for this purpose. Orders are placed through MD Toolbox embedded in Chasers; Kelley-Ross can see the Chasers record for injectables but not for tablets/films.

